    <body>

        <div xml:id="AN141.1-kilavi1">
          <p type="edition">piriviṭai yāṟṟāḷeṉak kavaṉṟa tōḻikkut <app><lem>talaimakaḷ</lem><rdg wit="#C2 #C3 #C7 #RK">kiḻatti</rdg></app> <app><lem>colliyatu</lem><rdg wit="#RK">yuraittatu</rdg></app>.</p>
          <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">What SHE said to the confidante who was anxious that she would not have the strength in the time of separation.</p>
        </div>
        <div xml:id="AN141.1-kilavi2">
          <p type="edition">āṟṟāḷeṉak kavaṉṟa tōḻikkut talaimakaḷ colliyatūumām.</p>
          <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">What SHE said to the confidante who was anxious that she would not have the strength.</p>
        </div>
        <div xml:id="AN141.1-kilavi3"> <!-- This may be not a separate kilavi, we should clear that, and its place. Made a note in Word too. -->
          <p type="edition">C2+3+9: aṟumīṉeṉṟa turōkaṇimīṉ (C9: urōkiṇimīṉai).</p>
          <p type="translation" xml:lang="en"></p>
        </div>

        <div xml:id="AN141.1">
            <lg type="edition">
                <l>amma vāḻi tōḻi kaimmika<supplied>k</supplied></l>
                <l>kaṉavuṅ kaṅkuṟō ṟiṉiya naṉṟum</l>
                <l>puṉaiviṉai nalliṟ puḷḷum pāṅkiṉa</l>
                <l>neñcu naṉipukaṉ ṟuṟai<supplied>yu</supplied> meñcā</l>
                <l>tulakutoḻi lulantu nāñci ṟuñcu</l>
                <l>maḻaikā ṉīṅkiya māka vicumpiṟ</l>
                <l>kuṟumuya<supplied>ṉ</supplied> maṟuniṟaṅ kiḷara mati<supplied>ni</supplied>ṟain</l>
                <l>ta<supplied>ṟu</supplied>mīṉ cēru makaliru ṇaṭunā<supplied>ṇ</supplied></l>
                <l>maṟukuviḷak kuṟuttu mālai <supplied>tū</supplied>kkip</l>
                <l>pa<supplied>ḻampaṉ</supplied> mūtūrp palaruṭaṉ ṟuvaṉṟi</l>
                <l>viḻavuṭa ṉayara varukati<supplied>l</supplied> lamma</l>
                <l>tuvarap pula<supplied>r</supplied>ntu tūmalar kañalit</l>
                <l>takara nāṟun taṇṇaṟuṅ katu<supplied>p</supplied>piṟ</l>
                <l>putumaṇa makaṭūu vayiṉiya kaṭinaka<supplied>r</supplied>p</l>
                <l>palkōṭ ṭa<supplied>ṭu</supplied>ppiṟ pālulai yirīik</l>
                <l>kūḻai kūntaṟ kuṟuntoṭi makaḷir</l>
                <l>peruñcey nelliṉ vāṅkukatir murittup</l>
                <l>pācava liṭikku miruṅkā ḻulakkaik</l>
                <l>kaṭiyiṭi verīik kamañcūl veṇkuruku</l>
                <l>tīṅkulai vā<supplied>ḻai</supplied> yōṅkumaṭa lirātu</l>
                <l>neṭuṅkāṉ māttuk kuṟumpoṟai payiṟṟuñ</l>
                <l>celkuṭi niṟutta perumpeyark karikāl</l>
                <l>velpōrc cō<supplied>ḻa</supplied> ṉiṭaimā ṟaṉṉa</l>
                <l>nallicai veṟukkai tarumār palpoṟip</l>
                <l>pulikkē <supplied>ḻu</supplied>ṟṟa pūvuṭaip peruñciṉai</l>
                <l>naranta naṟumpū nāṇmala rutirak</l>
                <l>kalaipāyn tukaḷuṅ kal<supplied>latar</supplied> vēṅkait</l>
                <l>tēṅkamaḻ neṭuvarai piṟaṅkiya</l>
                <l>vēṅkaṭa veṟpiṟ <supplied>cura</supplied>ṉiṟan tōrē.</l>
            </lg>
            <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
                <l>Alas, oh friend. Every night</l>
                <l>[my] dreams are very sweet and well</l>
                <l>close to the good house of artful work[manship] are the birds, (1-3)</l>
                <l>and [my] heart keeps much rejoicing. Without exception (4)</l>
                <l>the works of the world have died down [and] the ploughs sleep. (5)</l>
                <l>At midnight in the vast darkness when the moon becomes full,</l>
                <l>so that that dirty colour of the small hare shines, [and] joins the six stars</l>
                <l>in the vast sky which clouds [and] wind have left, (6-8)</l>
                <l>when, kindling lamps in the streets, hanging up garlands, (9)</l>
                <l>many together fill up the old village where fruit are many, (10)</l> 
                <l>[and] together are engaged in a festival, would that he came, (11)</l>
                <l>– he who, in order to give famous riches, (24a-c)</l>
                <l rend="indent3">like Iṭaimāṟu, [place] of the Cōḻa of victorious battle, (23)</l>
                <l rend="indent3">Karikāl with great name who stopped the clans on the move(?), (22)</l>
                <l rend="indent4">where, frightened by the harrying thunder (19ab)</l>
                <l rend="indent4">of the large hard pestles that pound fresh rice, (18)</l>
                <l rend="indent4">breaking the bowing ears of paddy from the big fields, (17)</l>
                <l rend="indent5">[used by] women with small bangles [and] short tresses (16)</l>
                <l rend="indent5">after setting pots with milk on ovens with many curves, (15)</l>
                <l rend="indent5">[their] hair cool [and] fragrant, scented with unguent</l>
                <l rend="indent5">[and] dense with pure blossoms after having been divided [into strands and] dried,</l> 
                <l rend="indent6">the fully pregnant white ibis birds,</l>
                <l rend="indent5">no [longer] perch on the high fronds of the plantain tree with sweet [fruit] bunches,</l>
                <l rend="indent5">repeat [their calls] on the short hillocks of long-trunked mango trees, (12-21)</l>
                <l>has gone to traverse the desert of the Vēṅkaṭam mountains (29)</l>
                <l>that glisten with high peaks fragrant with the honey</l>
                <l>of kino trees on the stony road where monkeys leap [and] jump (27f.)</l>
                <l>when, from the big branches that possess flowers that have the lustre of the tiger with many dots,</l>
                <l>day[-fresh] blossoms drop on the fragrant flowers of the bitter orange. (24d-26)</l>
            </lg>
        </div>
